The grammar is in Chomsky Normal Form with no unit‐productions for non­terminals. Any derivation from S must produce exactly two terminals (one from each child in S→NT41 NT23 or NT41 NT58). Since “t64” is a single terminal, it cannot be generated.

We check the two ways to expand S in the CNF grammar:

1) S → NT41 NT23  
2) S → NT41 NT58  

Our target string is two tokens: t13 t83.  

– NT41 → 't13' (given)  
– NT23 → 't83' (given)  
– NT58 can only produce t17 or t74, so it cannot yield t83.  

Thus the only way is  
  S → NT41 NT23 → 't13' 't83'  

So the grammar does generate that string.  
Yes

To get exactly two terminals from S, it must use one of

  S → NT41 NT23  
  S → NT41 NT58

and each NT must directly produce a terminal (since the input has length 2).  The only non‐terminals that produce t62 are NT43 and NT35—but neither appears in an S‐production.  NT41, NT23, and NT58 cannot produce t62 as a single terminal, so there is no way for S ⇒* t62 t62.

To derive a two‐token string in CNF, S must split as S→A B, with A⇒t71 and B⇒t64 in one step each. The only productions for S are

  S → NT41 NT23  
  S → NT41 NT58

so A must be NT41. But NT41 only produces the terminal t13 (and a two‐nonterminal expansion), never t71. Hence no derivation yields t71 t64.

We attempt a CKY‐style split of the length‐3 string t13 t71 t49 from S. The only top‐level productions are

  S → NT41 NT23  
  S → NT41 NT58  

The first symbol is t13, and the only rule that gives t13 is  
  NT41 → 't13'.  

Hence S must use NT41 to cover the first symbol, and we have two cases:

1. S → NT41 NT23  
   • NT41 → t13 covers the first symbol.  
   • NT23 can only produce a single terminal (t83 or t19), so it cannot cover the two‐symbol suffix t71 t49.  

2. S → NT41 NT58  
   • Again NT41 → t13 covers the first symbol.  
   • We need NT58 ⇒ t71 t49. NT58 has the binary production  
       NT58 → NT15 NT24  
     and terminal productions, but the only way to get two symbols is via NT15 NT24.  
     • NT15 → 't71' covers the second symbol.  
     • NT24 → 't49' covers the third symbol.  

Thus S ⇒ NT41 NT58 ⇒ 't13' (NT15 NT24) ⇒ t13 t71 t49. The string is in the language.  

Yes

The grammar is in CNF, so any 3‐token string must come from exactly two binary productions (internal nodes) and the rest terminal productions. From the start rules

1) S → NT41 NT23  
2) S → NT41 NT58

to get three leaves, exactly one of NT41/NT23 (resp. NT41/NT58) must be binary and the other unary. Checking both splits:

- S → NT41 NT23: NT23 only → 't83' or 't19', never 't66'.  
- S → NT41 NT58:  
  • If NT41 is unary it must be 't13' ≠ 't28'.  
  • If NT58 is unary it must be 't17' or 't74' ≠ 't66'.  

No assignment yields the required terminals t28 t33 t66.  
No

We need to split the 5‐token string under one of the two S‐rules:

1) S → NT41 NT23  
   NT23 is a single terminal ‘t83’ or ‘t19’, so it would have to match the 5th token t26.  It doesn’t.

2) S → NT41 NT58  
   NT58 can either be a single terminal (‘t17’ or ‘t74’) – doesn’t match t26 – or NT15 NT24 (two tokens).  In that latter case those two must cover the last two tokens (t19, t26).  NT15 must then yield t19, but NT15’s only terminals are t71 or t59, so it cannot match t19.  

No split works, so the string is not in the language.

After examining all ways to split the 5‐token input under the only two S‐rules (S→NT41 NT23 or S→NT41 NT58), in every case the required terminals (t14 t27 t24 t58 t17) fail to match the fixed outputs of NT41, NT23, or NT58. Hence the grammar cannot generate this string.

To generate any string, S must begin with NT41.  NT41 only ever expands to  
  either the single terminal t13  
  or to the two‐terminal sequence t26 t57  
so every string in L(G) starts with t13 or with t26.  The given string starts with t38, so it cannot be generated.

t59 t81 t24 t27 t38 t24

All used productions appear in the grammar, so the string is generated.

`t26 t57 t59 t83 t7 t22 t33 t7 t66`.  
Hence the grammar does not generate the string.

After examining the only two ways S can expand:

1. S → NT41 NT23.  
   NT23 only ever produces a single token: t83 or t19, but our string ends in t66.  

2. S → NT41 NT58.  
   NT58 has three productions:  
     • NT58 → 't17'  
     • NT58 → 't74'  
     • NT58 → NT15 NT24 (yielding exactly two tokens, each from NT15={t59,t71} and NT24={t49,t33,t27,t63})  

None of these can end (or even contain) t66, yet our string’s last token is t66. Thus there is no way for S to derive the given string.

But neither placement leads to a matching NT23 or NT58 on the rest of the 12‑token string, so S cannot derive the entire input.

After inspecting the start symbol S → NT41 NT58 (the only viable choice, since NT23 only yields a single terminal t83 or t19, which doesn’t match the final token), we see that NT41 can only expand as

1) NT41 → 't13'  
2) NT41 → NT34 NT49 → 't26' 't57'  
3) NT41 → NT41 NT5 (which just prepends more NT5‑blocks on one of the above bases)

In every case, the first terminal of NT41’s yield is either t13 or t26. But our input begins with t8. Hence there is no way to generate a string starting with t8 from NT41, so S cannot derive the given 12‐token string.

In particular, the only two‐token “NT15 NT24” fits fail, and the single‐token NT58→‘t17’/‘t74’ doesn’t match the final token t33.  Therefore the grammar cannot generate

  t13 t38 t64 t19 t26 t7 t66 t7 t66 t63 t49 t7 t33.

After examining the only ways S can expand—either S→NT41 NT23 or S→NT41 NT58—and noting that NT41 can only ever produce the two‐token string [t26 t57] (or the single terminal t13), there is no way to match the given prefix [t54 t57…].  Hence the string cannot be generated.

After inspecting the two possible top‐level productions,

  S → NT41 NT23  
  S → NT41 NT58

the yield of NT41 must begin with either

  • NT41 → 't13'  (i.e. t13), or  
  • NT41 → NT34 NT49 → 't26' …  

so any S‐derivation begins with t13 or t26.  The target string begins with t74, which NT41 cannot generate.  Therefore the grammar cannot produce this string.

After running through the only possible top‐level decomposition S→NT41 NT58 and checking all ways NT41 can consume the initial t13 and NT58 the remaining 13 tokens, every attempt ultimately fails (NT24 and NT28 can’t cover the variety of tokens in positions 3–14, and NT58’s other productions only yield single terminals t17 or t74). Hence the string cannot be derived.

After attempting to build a CYK‐style parse, the only way to get an initial NT41 is at position 1 “t13,” so we must use

  S → NT41 NT58  
  NT41 → “t13”

and then try to have NT58 ⇒ t59 … t66 over positions 2–14.  NT58 only has the split

  NT58 → NT15 NT24  
  NT15 → “t59”  
  NT24 → NT23 NT28

so positions 2–4 must be “t59 t83 …”, which they are.  But then NT28 must cover the remaining 11 tokens “t24 t54 t33 t24 t13 t28 t33 t24 t66 t7 t66,” and neither of its binary rules can yield that tail.  All other binary decompositions fail to match the required terminals in order, so NT58 cannot derive the last 13 symbols.  No other S‐production applies, so the string is not in the language.

After trying all possible splits S→NT41 NT58 (the only viable S‐rule here) and noting that NT41 has only two productions

  NT41 → 't13'  
  NT41 → NT34 NT49 → 't26' 't57'

it’s impossible for NT41 to derive the string’s first one or two terminals (which are “t59 t7”). Hence no derivation of the full string exists.

After examining both possible start‐rule expansions,

  1. S → NT41 NT23 forces NT23 to generate the final token “t33”, but NT23 can only be “t83” or “t19.”  
  2. S → NT41 NT58 forces NT58 to generate the last m tokens (m=2,3,4), and in every case we get a mismatch (for length=1,2,3,4 its terminals or binary children can’t line up with “t28 t33” or “t57 t28 t33”, etc.).  

No split of the 15‐token string between NT41 and NT58 or NT23 ever matches the required terminals.  Hence the grammar cannot generate the string.

After doing a CYK‐style check, the only way to start is  
S → NT41 NT58 with NT41 ⇒ t13 covering position 1.  That forces NT58 to cover positions 2–15.  One then finds NT58 ⇒ NT15 NT24 with NT15 ⇒ t71 at position 2, and NT24 ⇒ NT23 NT28 with NT23 ⇒ t83 at position 3 and NT28 forced to cover positions 4–15.  But every way you expand NT28 (through NT28→NT38 NT31 or NT28→NT18 NT2) eventually mis‐aligns with the required terminals (e.g. it needs NT32⇒t24 at a position holding t7, or NT2⇒t33 at a position holding t38).  And no other S‐split works (NT41 can only cover 1 token t13 or exactly 2 tokens t26 t57, so k=1 is the only viable split).  Hence no full derivation exists.  

No

We try both S‐productions:

1) S→NT41 NT23.  NT23 only ever yields the single terminal t83 or t19, so the entire string would have to end in t83 or t19 – but it ends in t74.  Impossible.

2) S→NT41 NT58.  
  • NT58 can yield the single terminal t17 or t74, or expand NT15 NT24.  
  – If NT58→t17 or t74, the string must end with exactly that one terminal.  Only t74 matches our last token, so NT58→t74 and NT41 would have to generate the first 14 tokens.  But NT41→NT34 NT49 forces the 14th token to be t57 (since NT49→t57), yet our 14th token is t62.  And NT41→t13 is just a single terminal.  
  – If NT58→NT15 NT24, NT15 must come from NT31 NT3 (giving exactly two tokens (t38|t66)(t63|t64)), but no adjacent pair in our tail matches one of those four pairs, so that expansion fails too.

Since neither S→NT41 NT23 nor S→NT41 NT58 can cover the 15‐token input, the string is not in the language.

After inspecting the start‐symbol productions

  S → NT41 NT23  
  S → NT41 NT58

and noting

  NT41 ⇒ either two terminals (via NT34,NT49) or the single terminal “t13”  
  NT23 ⇒ a single terminal (“t83” or “t19”)  
  NT58 ⇒ either one terminal (“t17” or “t74”) or exactly two terminals (via NT15 NT24)

S can only derive strings of length 3 or 4, but the input has length 15. Hence it cannot be generated.

After running a CYK‐style check you find

1. S can only start with NT41  
2. NT41 → NT34 NT49 is the only way to match "t26 t57" at positions 1–2  
3. That forces S → NT41 NT58, so NT58 must cover positions 3–16  
4. NT58 → NT15 NT24 is the only viable split at 3–16  
5. NT15 ⇒ NT31 NT3 exactly covers "t38 t63" at positions 3–4  
6. NT24 ⇒ NT23 NT28 covers "t83" at position 5 then NT28 must cover positions 6–16  
7. A deeper inspection shows NT28 can never match the 11 remaining tokens  

Hence the full string cannot be generated.

To generate S you must first derive NT41, but NT41 only comes from

  NT41 → NT34 NT49  
  NT41 → 't13'

NT34 requires the terminal t26 and NT49 requires t57, or else NT41 must match t13 directly. Since the input string contains neither t26 nor t57 nor t13, NT41 never appears in any substring of the input. Hence S cannot be derived.

After running through the possible splits for S → NT41 NT23 and S → NT41 NT58, there is no way to cover all 16 tokens so that the left part derives NT41 and the right part derives NT23 or NT58. Hence the string is not in the language.

After inspecting the productions for NT41, we see NT41 only ever expands to either the single terminal t13 or exactly two terminals (via NT34 NT49).  In our target string the first two tokens are t11, t17, which cannot match NT41 → t13 nor NT41 → NT34 NT49 (which would give t26 t57).  No longer expansion of NT41 is possible (it has no recursive rules), so S → NT41 … cannot cover the initial t11 t17.  Hence the full string cannot be derived.

We only ever combine NT41 with either NT23 (which only ever yields a single terminal, t83 or t19) or NT58 (which either directly yields a single terminal t17 or t74, or via NT58→NT15 NT24 yields exactly two terminals).  Our target string ends in t66, not t19, t83, t17, or t74, so neither S→NT41 NT23 nor S→NT41 NT58 can cover that last symbol (even allowing the two‐symbol NT15 NT24 expansion).  Hence no split of the 17 tokens can match the start rule.

After attempting to carry out a CYK‐style (or top‐down) decomposition, one finds that the only way to start is

  S ⇒ NT41 NT58  
  NT41 ⇒ t13  
  NT58 ⇒ NT15 NT24  
    NT15 ⇒ t59  
    NT24 ⇒ NT23 NT28 ⇒ t83 …  

and so on.  But no matter how you choose splits in the long NT24 → NT23 NT28 → … → NT37 → NT58 NT32 chains, you eventually reach a point where the required NT15 = t59|t71 cannot align with the actual token in the string.  In particular, after matching the first t59 at position 2 and the only other t71 at position 12, the next recursive expansion of NT58 would have to begin on a token that is neither t59 nor t71, which is impossible.  Thus the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

After running through the possible CYK‐style splits, the only way to get NT41 out of the first two tokens is

  S → NT41 NT58  
  NT41 → NT34 NT49  
   NT34 → t26, NT49 → t57  

so NT41 covers t26 t57.  That forces NT58 to cover the remaining 15 tokens

  t71 t19 t24 t9 t33 t24 t66 t24 t66 t7 t66 t7 t74 t7 t33  

but NT58’s only non‐terminal production is  
  NT58 → NT15 NT24  

and NT15 can only generate 1 or 2 tokens (either a single t71/t59 or two tokens via NT31 NT3), while NT24 at best can generate one terminal plus whatever NT28 can muster via its recursion.  A detailed check of all binary splits shows no way to stretch NT15 to cover the needed prefix nor to make NT24+NT28 pick up the full 14 or 13 remaining terminals.  Hence the suffix cannot be derived by NT58, so the whole string cannot be derived from S.

After checking all possible derivations from S, the longest string it can produce is of length 5, far short of the given 17‐token string. Therefore, the string is not in the language.

After applying S → NT41 NT58 with NT41 → “t13” and NT58 → NT15 NT24 (the only way to match the prefix “t13 t38 t64”), one must have

· NT15 ⇒ t38 t64 (via NT15→NT31 NT3)  
· NT24 ⇒ t83 … t33 (via NT23⇒t83 then NT28)

and NT28 would have to generate 13 terminals 
[t26 t7 t26 t57 t24 t81 t35 t24 t81 t26 t57 t28] before NT2⇒t33.  
But a case‐by‐case CYK check shows no valid split for NT28—none of its productions can cover that 13‐token stretch.  And the alternative S→NT41 NT23 or NT58⇒a single terminal also cannot match a 17‑token string.  Therefore the grammar cannot generate the given string.

After running a (manual) CYK‐style check, the only possible top‐level expansion for S that could reach a 17‐token string is

  S → NT41 NT58  
  NT41 → 't13'  (covers token 1)  
  NT58 → NT15 NT24  

which forces

  NT15 → NT31 NT3  covering tokens 2–3 (t38 t64),  
  NT24 → NT23 NT28 covering tokens 4–17.

NT23 can match token 4 = t83, leaving NT28 to cover tokens 5–17.  
NT28 has only three rules:

  (a) NT28 → 't26'  
  (b) NT28 → NT38 NT31  
  (c) NT28 → NT18 NT2  

(a) gives length 1 only, too short.  
(b) forces the last token of 5–17 (t33) to come from NT31 which can only be t38 or t66 – mismatch.  
(c) forces the last token of 5–17 to come from NT2 = 't33' (good) but then NT18 must cover tokens 5–16.  Checking NT18’s two expansions

  NT18 → NT32 NT36  (only length 2, too short)  
  NT18 → NT38 NT37

fails because NT37 (the suffix) cannot match the final token of that span (t7).  

No other splits work out. Hence the grammar cannot generate the 17‐token string.

After examining the start‐rules

  S → NT41 NT23  
  S → NT41 NT58

we see NT41 has only two productions:

  NT41 → NT34 NT49  
  NT41 → 't13'

and NT34 → 't26', NT49 → 't57'.  Hence NT41 can generate only either the single terminal "t13" or the two‐terminal string "t26 t57".  But our input begins "t33 …", so NT41 cannot match that prefix.  Therefore S cannot generate the given string.

 S ⇒ NT41 NT58  
 ⇒ NT41 NT15 NT24  
 ⇒ (t26 t57) (t66 t63) NT24  
 ⇒ … ⇒ t26 t57 t66 t63 t83 ⋯

so NT24 must cover

   t83 t7 t24 t38 t63 t33 t24 t33 t24 t38 t7 t66 t7 t38

by the rule NT24→NT23 NT28, giving NT28→…  
But any path through NT28’s binary rules (NT28→NT38 NT31 or NT18 NT2) forces the final element of each span to be produced by NT31 or NT2. NT31 only yields t38 or t66, NT2 only t33, yet we need to produce t63 in one of those positions. No choice of productions can generate that t63 in the needed slot. Hence the grammar cannot derive the full 18‐token string.

  S → NT41 NT58  
  NT41 ⇒ t26 t57  (covers positions 1–2)  
  NT58 → NT15 NT24

     NT24 → NT23 NT28  
       NT23 ⇒ t19 (position 4)  
       NT28 must then cover positions 5–18, but no sequence of NT28’s two binary rules can consume the 14 symbols t24 t9 t33 t7 t38 t7 t13 t26 t57 t66 t33 t24 t84 t33 successfully (all other splits fail either because NT3, NT31 or NT2 cannot match the required terminals or because the needed lengths don’t line up).  No other top‐level split of S works (NT23 can only derive one of {t19,t83}, so S→NT41 NT23 fails on the last symbol t33).

Thus the grammar does not generate the given string.

After attempting a CYK‐style reconstruction, the only way to expand S is

  S → NT41 NT58  
  NT41 ⇒ t13 covers position 1, so NT58 must cover positions 2–18.

But NT58 (a nonterminal) only has the binary rule

  NT58 → NT15 NT24

and NT15 must cover exactly two symbols. Checking all possible splits forces NT15→NT31 NT3 to cover positions 2–3, leaving NT24 to cover positions 4–18.  NT24 in turn can only be built as NT23 NT28, so NT23 must cover position 4 and NT28 must cover 5–18.  However, NT28’s only binary decompositions cannot stretch to cover positions 5–18 (the final token t66 cannot be paired correctly in any of its right‐hand sides), and no chain of NT28→… rules can produce a span of length 14 ending in t66.

Thus there is no way to derive all 18 terminals under the given CNF grammar. The string is not generated.

After inspecting the productions, one sees that

• NT41 can only generate the single terminal “t13” or the 2‐terminal sequence “t26 t57.”  
• NT23 only ever yields a single terminal (“t83” or “t19”).  
• NT58 either yields one of the single terminals “t17” or “t74” or else at most 4 terminals via its one binary rule (NT58→NT15 NT24), but NT15 itself can only yield at most 2 terminals and NT24 at most 2.

Hence S → NT41 NT23 can only produce 1+1 or 2+1=3 terminals, and S → NT41 NT58 can only produce at most 2+4=6 terminals. It is impossible to generate an 18‐token string.

There are no adjacent pairs in the input matching that pattern, so NT15 cannot cover any part of the string. Hence neither S→NT41 NT23 nor S→NT41 NT58 can derive the 18‐token input.

Consequently no larger spans covering those two tokens can be built, so S cannot derive the entire string.

Hence no valid parse exists.

We first observe that the only way for S to cover 19 terminals is by the second production

  S → NT41 NT58

because the other option, S → NT41 NT23, would force the last terminal to be t83 or t19 (the only ones NT23 can produce), but our last terminal is t66.  Hence we must split the string as

  [1]             [2–19]
  t13    |  t38 t63 t19 t7 t24 t26 t57 t26 t57 t66 t62 t62 t62 t33 t7 t38 t24 t66
   |           |
  NT41        NT58

1.  NT41 ⇒ 't13' covers the first symbol (NT41 also has a binary rule NT34 NT49 ⇒ t26 t57, but that would produce “t26 t57,” which does not match “t13,” so the only choice is NT41→'t13').  
2.  NT58 must cover the remaining 18 symbols.  It cannot produce a single terminal (it only has 't17' or 't74' as single‐terminal rules, but our suffix starts with t38), so it must use its binary rule

     NT58 → NT15 NT24.
